><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; color: #0433ff;">ID</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">,</span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">‘</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; color: #ff40ff;">title_li</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">’ =&gt; ‘’      /* Removes the keyword “Pages”  */</span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;"> ); </span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">?&gt;</span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">        </span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">&lt;?php wp_list_pages($args); ?&gt;</span></div><div><br /></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">However, when you click on one of the child list, the list will disappear because of the fact that the child has no its own children.</span></div><div><br /></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">To make the list to show up even when we click on the child list, the above code need to be modified:</span></div><div><br /></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">&lt;?php</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">  $args = </span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">array</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">( </span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">‘</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; color: #ff40ff;">child_of</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">’ =&gt; </span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; color: #aa7942; font-weight: bold;">get_top_ancestor_id()</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">,  /* We need to create this function in our “functions.php file */</span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">‘</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica; color: #ff40ff;">title_li</span><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;">’ =&gt; ‘’      /* Removes the keyword “Pages”  */</span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helvetica;"> ); </span></div><div><span style="font: 12.0px Helv